# 5. Producing seamless procedural textures

For reliable tileability, use periodic noise rather than merely blending image edges.

Map a two-dimensional texture coordinate onto a four-dimensional periodic domain:

```text
x = cos(2πu)
y = sin(2πu)
z = cos(2πv)
w = sin(2πv)
```

Then sample four-dimensional noise:

```rust
fn periodic_point(uv: Vec2) -> [f32; 4] {
    let u = uv.x * std::f32::consts::TAU;
    let v = uv.y * std::f32::consts::TAU;

    [u.cos(), u.sin(), v.cos(), v.sin()]
}
```

Because `u = 0` and `u = 1` map to the same position, the resulting texture tiles exactly.

The texture baker should also run automated seam tests:

```rust
fn maximum_texture_seam_error(
    image: &GeneratedImage,
) -> f32 {
    let horizontal = compare_left_and_right_edges(image);
    let vertical = compare_top_and_bottom_edges(image);

    horizontal.max(vertical)
}
```

Fail the bake when the error exceeds a configured tolerance.

