# 14. Triplanar projection

Planar UVs break on:

* vertical cliffs,
* cave walls,
* cave ceilings,
* overhang undersides,
* natural arches.

Your volumetric terrain design already identifies triplanar mapping as the appropriate solution for these surfaces. 

Basic triplanar weights:

```wgsl
fn triplanar_weights(
    normal: vec3<f32>,
    sharpness: f32,
) -> vec3<f32> {
    var weights = pow(abs(normal), vec3(sharpness));
    return weights / max(
        weights.x + weights.y + weights.z,
        0.0001,
    );
}
```

Basic array sampling:

```wgsl
fn sample_triplanar_color(
    texture_array: texture_2d_array<f32>,
    texture_sampler: sampler,
    world_position: vec3<f32>,
    world_normal: vec3<f32>,
    layer: u32,
    meters_per_repeat: f32,
    sharpness: f32,
) -> vec4<f32> {
    let scale = 1.0 / meters_per_repeat;
    let weights =
        triplanar_weights(world_normal, sharpness);

    let x_sample = textureSample(
        texture_array,
        texture_sampler,
        world_position.yz * scale,
        layer,
    );

    let y_sample = textureSample(
        texture_array,
        texture_sampler,
        world_position.xz * scale,
        layer,
    );

    let z_sample = textureSample(
        texture_array,
        texture_sampler,
        world_position.xy * scale,
        layer,
    );

    return
        x_sample * weights.x
        + y_sample * weights.y
        + z_sample * weights.z;
}
```

Normal maps require extra work. Each projected tangent-space normal must be reoriented into world space before blending:

```text
X projection:
normal interpreted relative to Y/Z plane

Y projection:
normal interpreted relative to X/Z plane

Z projection:
normal interpreted relative to X/Y plane
```

Blend those reoriented normals and normalize the result.

Do not simply blend the encoded RGB values of all three normal samples.

