# 23. Hot reload and invalidation

Changes should propagate through dependencies.

```text
Texture recipe changed
    ↓
Rebake texture
    ↓
Repack affected array
    ↓
Update GPU image
    ↓
Do not remesh terrain

Surface scale changed
    ↓
Update material parameters
    ↓
Do not rebake texture

Classifier rule changed
    ↓
Reclassify affected material regions
    ↓
Update vertex blend weights
    ↓
Remesh or update mesh attributes

Biome definition changed
    ↓
Recompute biome field
    ↓
Reclassify affected regions
```

Bevy tracks asset changes and emits asset events; its asset collections can also be queried for changed underlying assets. ([Docs.rs][5])

Maintain an explicit dependency index:

```rust
pub struct MaterialDependencyIndex {
    pub texture_to_surfaces:
        HashMap<TextureSetId, Vec<SurfaceId>>,

    pub surface_to_classifiers:
        HashMap<SurfaceId, Vec<ClassifierId>>,

    pub classifier_to_regions:
        HashMap<ClassifierId, HashSet<MaterialRegionCoord>>,
}
```

---

# 24. Asynchronous work pipeline

Do not bake textures or classify thousands of vertices on the render thread.

```text
Main thread:
Detect asset or terrain change
Create immutable job input

Worker task:
Compile definitions
Bake texture pixels
Classify surface samples
Build mesh attributes

Main thread:
Insert or update Bevy assets
Replace material handles
Replace mesh attributes
```

Bevy assets and render resources should be created or updated through the application world. Worker tasks should return plain Rust data such as:

```rust
pub struct GeneratedTextureSet {
    pub albedo: PixelBuffer,
    pub normal_height: PixelBuffer,
    pub orm: PixelBuffer,
}

pub struct ClassifiedChunkMaterials {
    pub weights_0: Vec<[f32; 4]>,
    pub weights_1: Vec<[f32; 4]>,
    pub palette: MaterialRegionPalette,
}
```

---

# 25. Storage buffers and shared palettes

The initial implementation can create one material asset for each material-region palette.

A more advanced implementation can keep one shared material and store many palettes in a GPU storage buffer:

```rust
pub struct GpuMaterialRegionPalette {
    pub layer_indices_0: [u32; 4],
    pub layer_indices_1: [u32; 4],
    pub scales_0: [f32; 4],
    pub scales_1: [f32; 4],
}
```

Each chunk receives a palette index through an instance tag or custom per-instance data.

Bevy’s current examples demonstrate binding a `ShaderBuffer` to a custom material through `AsBindGroup`, as well as using `MeshTag` to select data inside the shader. ([Bevy][6])

Treat this as an optimization phase. The simpler per-region material handles are easier to debug.

